Step 1 — Pull and run Nagios container

On Windows PowerShell:

docker pull jasonrivers/nagios:latest
docker run --name nagios4 -p 8090:80 -d jasonrivers/nagios:latest


Open Nagios in browser:

http://localhost:8090/nagios


Default login:

User: nagiosadmin
Pass: nagios

Step 2 — Enter the Nagios container shell
docker exec -it nagios4 bash


Inside the container, configs are at /opt/nagios/etc/objects.

Step 3 — Install an editor (nano) if needed

This container has no editor by default. Install nano:

apt-get update
apt-get install nano -y

Step 4 — Add a simple monitoring check

Go to config folder:

cd /opt/nagios/etc/objects


Open localhost.cfg:

nano localhost.cfg


Scroll to the bottom and add this exact block:

define service{
    use                     local-service
    host_name               localhost
    service_description     Check Google
    check_command           check_http!www.google.com
}


Save & exit:

Press CTRL+O → ENTER → CTRL+X

Step 5 — Exit container
exit

Step 6 — Restart Nagios container to apply changes

From Windows host PowerShell (not inside container):

docker restart nagios4

Step 7 — Verify Nagios monitoring

Open in browser:

http://localhost:8090/nagios


Go to:

Services → All Services


Look for Check Google. Status meanings:

GREEN = OK → Google is reachable

RED = DOWN → Google unreachable

ORANGE = WARNING → problem detected
